IF ntp is in use on the system, run the following command to verify the restrict lines: # grep -P -- '^\h*restrict\h+((-4\h+)?|- 6\h+)default\h+(?:[^#
]+\h+)*(?!(?:\2|\3|\4|\5))(\h* kod \h*|\h* nomodi fy \h*|\h* notrap \h*|\h* nopeer \h*|\h* noquery \h*)\h+(?:[^#
]+\h +)*(?!(?:\1|\3|\4|\5))(\h* kod \h*|\h* nomodify \h*|\h* notrap \h*|\h*\ bnopeer \h*|\h* noquery \h*)\h+(?:[^#
]+\h+)*(?!(?:\1|\2|\4|\5))(\h* k od \h*|\h* nomodify \h*|\h* notrap \h*|\h* nopeer \h*|\h* noquery \h *)\h+(?:[^#
]+\h+)*(?!(?:\1|\2|\3|\5))(\h* kod \h*|\h* nomodify \h*|\h * notrap \h*|\h* nopeer \h*|\h* noquery \h*)\h+(?:[^#
]+\h+)*(?!(?:\ 1|\2|\3|\4))(\h* kod \h*|\h* nomodify \h*|\h* notrap \h*|\h* nopeer \ h*|\h* noquery \h*)\h*(?:\h+\H+\h*)*(?:\h+#.*)?$' /etc/ntp.conf Output should be similar to: restrict -4 default kod notrap nomodify nopeer noquery restrict -6 default kod notrap nomodify nopeer noquery Verify that the output includes two lines, and both lines include: default, kod, nomodify, notrap, nopeer and noquery. Note: The -4 in the first line is optional, options after default may appear in any order, and additional options may exist.
